05064nam a22009495i 9780520940802DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20052005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696641  a97805209408027 a10.1525/97805209408022doi  a(DE-B1597)519467  a(OCoLC)61730535  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aML275 4aML 7aMUS0060002bisacsh1 aFrisch, Walter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGerman Modernism :bMusic and the Arts /cWalter Frisch. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (332 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in 20th-Century Music ;v300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Ambivalent Modernism -- tTwo. German Naturalism -- tThree. Convergences -- tFour. Bach, Regeneration, And Historicist Modernism -- tFive. Ironic Germans -- tSix. “Dancing In Chains” -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this pioneering, erudite study of a pivotal era in the arts, Walter Frisch examines music and its relationship to early modernism in the Austro-German sphere. Seeking to explore the period on its own terms, Frisch questions the common assumption that works created from the later 1870s through World War I were transitional between late romanticism and high modernism. Drawing on a wide range of examples across different media, he establishes a cultural and intellectual context for late Richard Wagner, Richard Strauss, Gustav Mahler, and Arnold Schoenberg, as well as their less familiar contemporaries Eugen d'Albert, Hans Pfitzner, Max Reger, Max von Schillings, and Franz Schreker.Frisch explores "ambivalent" modernism in the last quarter of the nineteenth century as reflected in the attitudes of, and relationship between, Nietzsche and Wagner. He goes on to examine how naturalism, the first self-conscious movement of German modernism, intersected with musical values and practices of the day. He proposes convergences between music and the visual arts in the works of Brahms, Max Klinger, Schoenberg, and Kandinsky. Frisch also explains how, near the turn of the century, composers drew inspiration and techniques from music of the past—the Renaissance, Bach, Mozart, and Wagner. Finally, he demonstrates how irony became a key strategy in the novels and novellas of Thomas Mann, the symphonies of Mahler, and the operas of Strauss and Hofmannsthal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArt and music. 0aModernism (Art)zGermany. 0aModernism (Music)zGermany. 0aMusiczGermanyy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiczGermanyy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  a19th century european music.  a20th century european music.  aambivalent modernism.  aarnold schoenberg.  aaustro german music.  acalifornia studies in 20th century music.  aearly modernism.  aeugen dalbert.  afranz schreker.  agerman modernism.  agerman naturalism.  agustav mahler.  ahans pfitzner.  ahistoricist modernism.  alate richard wagner.  amax reger.  amax von schillings.  amodernism.  amodernist music.  amodernity.  amusic and visual arts.  amusic history.  amusic.  amusicians.  anietzsche.  arichard strauss.  athomas mann.  awagner.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025148940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094080240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940802423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520940802/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  Universit